    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In computational parsing, when a parser is faced with this ambiguity, it doesn't just rely on a vague \"semantic plausibility\" feeling; it relies on probabilities derived from statistical models, often using techniques like Probabilistic Context-Free Grammars (PCFGs). It's like a giant, messy ledger where every possible combination of words has a certain likelihood of occurring based on how often they've appeared in massive amounts of text.\n\nThe parser calculates the probability of the entire sentence structure given the words it sees. It essentially calculates: $P(\\text{Structure} | \\text{Sentence})$.\n\nIf the grammar has two competing rules—one allowing the PP to attach to the NP and another allowing it to attach to the VP—the parser assigns a probability score to each resulting tree. The structure with the higher overall probability wins, even if the semantic interpretation seems slightly less intuitive to a human.\n\nThink of it like this: the parser is a very diligent, but slightly paranoid, accountant who has seen millions of sentences. It doesn't *understand* what a telescope is, but it knows that in 90% of sentences where a verb like \"saw\" is followed by a noun phrase, the modifying phrase tends",
